# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: additive-manufacturing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In the 1980s, 3D printing techniques were considered suitable only for the production of functional or aesthetic prototypes, and a more appropriate term for it at the time was rapid prototyping.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] As of 2019, the precision, repeatability, and material range of 3D printing have increased to the point that some 3D printing processes are considered viable as an industrial-production technology; in this context, the term *additive manufacturing* can be used synonymously with *3D printing*.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] One of the key advantages of 3D printing is the ability to produce very complex shapes or geometries that would be otherwise infeasible to construct by hand, including hollow parts or parts with internal truss structures to reduce weight while creating less material waste.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Fused deposition modeling (FDM), which uses a continuous filament of a thermoplastic material, is the most common 3D printing process in use as of 2020.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The umbrella term *additive manufacturing (AM)* gained popularity in the 2000s, inspired by the theme of material being added together (in any of various ways).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In contrast, the term *subtractive manufacturing* appeared as a retronym for the large family of machining processes with material *removal* as their common process.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* still referred only to the polymer technologies in most minds, and the term *AM* was more likely to be used in metalworking and end-use part production contexts than among polymer, inkjet, or stereolithography enthusiasts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Until recently, the term *3D printing* has been associated with machines low in price or capability.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] *3D printing* and *additive manufacturing* reflect that the technologies share the theme of material addition or joining throughout a 3D work envelope under automated control.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Other terms that have been used as synonyms or hypernyms have included *desktop manufacturing*, *rapid manufacturing* (as the logical production-level successor to *rapid prototyping*), and *on-demand manufacturing* (which echoes *on-demand printing* in the 2D sense of *printing*).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Today, the term *subtractive* has not replaced the term *machining*, instead complementing it when a term that covers any removal method is needed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Agile tooling is the use of modular means to design tooling that is produced by additive manufacturing or 3D printing methods to enable quick prototyping and responses to tooling and fixture needs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Agile tooling uses a cost-effective and high-quality method to quickly respond to customer and market needs, and it can be used in hydroforming, stamping, injection molding and other manufacturing processes.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Although the terms 3D printing and additive manufacturing can both be seen as the same thing, some standards organizitons make a distinction between them.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The American National Standards Institute (ANSI) says that international standards such as IS0/ASTM 52900 define additive manufacturing as the process of building parts from 3D model data and adding material layer by layer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In comparison, 3D printing is described as creating objects by depositing material through a print head or some variation of a nozzle type of device.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In industrial and technical settings, additive manufacturing is often the preferred term, and 3D printing is used more by the general public.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The general concept of and procedure to be used in 3D-printing was first described by Murray Leinster in his 1945 short story "Things Pass By": "But this constructor is both efficient and flexible.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] I feed magnetronic plastics — the stuff they make houses and ships of nowadays — into this moving arm.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] It makes drawings in the air following drawings it scans with photo-cells.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Jones in his story, "Tools of the Trade", published in the November 1950 issue of *Astounding Science Fiction* magazine.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] He referred to it as a "molecular spray" in that story.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 1971, Johannes F Gottwald patented the Liquid Metal Recorder, U.S. patent 3596285A, a continuous inkjet metal material device to form a removable metal fabrication on a reusable surface for immediate use or salvaged for printing again by remelting.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This appears to be the first patent describing 3D printing with rapid prototyping and controlled on-demand manufacturing of patterns.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Jones laid out the concept of 3D printing in his regular column *Ariadne* in the journal *New Scientist*.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Early additive manufacturing equipment and materials were developed in the 1980s.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In April 1980, Hideo Kodama of Nagoya Municipal Industrial Research Institute invented two additive methods for fabricating three-dimensional plastic models with photo-hardening thermoset polymer, where the UV exposure area is controlled by a mask pattern or a scanning fiber transmitter.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] He filed a patent for this XYZ plotter, which was published on 10 November 1981.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] His research results as journal papers were published in April and November 1981.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] However, there was no reaction to the series of his publications.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] His device was not highly evaluated in the laboratory and his boss did not show any interest.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] His research budget was just 60,000 yen or $545 a year.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Acquiring the patent rights for the XYZ plotter was abandoned, and the project was terminated.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] On 2 July 1984, American entrepreneur Bill Masters filed a patent for his computer automated manufacturing process and system (US 4665492).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This filing is on record at the USPTO as the first 3D printing patent in history; it was the first of three patents belonging to Masters that laid the foundation for the 3D printing systems used today.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] On 16 July 1984, Alain Le Méhauté, Olivier de Witte, and Jean Claude André filed their patent for the stereolithography process.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The application of the French inventors was abandoned by the French General Electric Company (now Alcatel-Alsthom) and CILAS (The Laser Consortium).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The claimed reason was "for lack of business perspective".
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Research (later named Howtek, Inc. in February 1984) to develop Pixelmaster, a color inkjet 2D printer using Thermoplastic (hot-melt) plastic ink, which was commercialized in 1986.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A team was put together, 6 members from Exxon Office Systems, Danbury Systems Division, an inkjet printer startup and some members of Howtek, Inc group who became popular figures in the 3D printing industry.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] One Howtek member was Richard Helinski, responsible for patent US5136515A ("Method and Means for constructing three-dimensional articles by particle deposition", application 7 November 1989 granted 4 August 1992).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] He formed C.A.D-Cast, Inc (later renamed to Visual Impact Corporation (VIC) on 22 August 1991), a New Hampshire company.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The company's prototype VIC 3D printer is available with a video presentation showing a 3D model printed with a single nozzle inkjet.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Another employee, Herbert Menhennett, formed HM Research, a New Hampshire company, in 1991 and introduced the Howtek, Inc, inkjet technology and thermoplastic materials to Royden Sanders of SDI and Bill Masters of Ballistic Particle Manufacturing (BPM), where he worked for a number of years.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Both BPM 3D printers and SPI 3D printers use Howtek, Inc style Inkjets and materials.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] McMahon, who was hired by Howtek, Inc to help develop the inkjet, later worked at Sanders Prototype and now operates Layer Grown Model Technology, a 3D service provider specializing in Howtek single nozzle inkjet and SDI printer support.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] McMahon worked with Steven Zoltan, inventor of the 1972 drop-on-demand inkjet at Exxon and holder of a 1978 patent that expanded the understanding of the single nozzle design inkjets (Alpha jets), to help perfect the Howtek, Inc hot-melt inkjets.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This Howtek hot-melt thermoplastic technology is popular with metal investment casting, especially in the 3D printing jewelry industry.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Royden Sanders licensed the Helinksi patent prior to manufacturing the Modelmaker 6 Pro at Sanders prototype, Inc (SPI) in 1993.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The first customer of the Modelmaker 6Pro was Hitchner Corporations, Metal Casting Technology, Inc in Milford, New Hampshire, a mile from the SDI facility in late 1993–1995 casting golf clubs and auto engine parts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Hull defined the process as a "system for generating three-dimensional objects by creating a cross-sectional pattern of the object to be formed".
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Hull's contribution was the STL (Stereolithography) file format and the digital slicing and infill strategies common to many processes today.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 1986, Charles "Chuck" Hull was granted a patent for this system, and his company, 3D Systems Corporation was formed and it released the first commercial 3D printer, the SLA-1, later in 1987 or 1988.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The technology used by most 3D printers to date—especially hobbyist and consumer-oriented models—is fused deposition modeling, a special application of plastic extrusion, developed in 1988 by S.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Scott Crump and commercialized by his company Stratasys, which marketed its first FDM machine in 1992.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] AM processes for metal sintering or melting (such as selective laser sintering, direct metal laser sintering, and selective laser melting) usually went by their own individual names in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] However, the automated techniques that *added* metal, which would later be called additive manufacturing, were beginning to challenge that assumption.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] By the mid-1990s, new techniques for material deposition were developed at Stanford and Carnegie Mellon University, including microcasting and sprayed materials.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Sacrificial and support materials had also become more common, enabling new object geometries.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The term *3D printing* originally referred to a powder bed process employing standard and custom inkjet print heads, developed at MIT by Emanuel Sachs in 1993 and commercialized by Soligen Technologies, Extrude Hone Corporation, and Z Corporation.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The year 1993 also saw the start of an inkjet 3D printer company initially named Sanders Prototype, Inc and later named Solidscape, introducing a high-precision polymer jet fabrication system with soluble support structures, (categorized as a "dot-on-dot" technique).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 1995 the Fraunhofer Society developed the selective laser melting process.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In the early 2000s 3D printers were still largely being used just in the manufacturing and research industries, as the technology was still relatively young and was too expensive for most consumers to be able to get their hands on.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The 2000s was when larger scale use of the technology began being seen in industry, most often in the architecture and medical industries, though it was typically used for low accuracy modeling and testing, rather than the production of common manufactured goods or heavy prototyping.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 2005 users began to design and distribute plans for 3D printers that could print around 70% of their own parts, the original plans of which were designed by Adrian Bowyer at the University of Bath in 2004, with the name of the project being RepRap (Replicating Rapid-prototyper).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2006 the Fab@Home project was started by Evan Malone and Hod Lipson, another project whose purpose was to design a low-cost and open source fabrication system that users could develop on their own and post feedback on, making the project very collaborative.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Much of the software for 3D printing available to the public at the time was open source, and as such was quickly distributed and improved upon by many individual users.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 2009 the Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) printing process patents expired.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This opened the door to a new wave of startup companies, many of which were established by major contributors of these open source initiatives, with the goal of many of them being to start developing commercial FDM 3D printers that were more accessible to the general public.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] As the various additive processes matured, it became clear that soon metal removal would no longer be the only metalworking process done through a tool or head moving through a 3D work envelope, transforming a mass of raw material into a desired shape layer by layer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The 2010s were the first decade in which metal end-use parts such as engine brackets and large nuts would be grown (either before or instead of machining) in job production rather than obligately being machined from bar stock or plate.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] One place that AM is making a significant inroad is in the aviation industry.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] With nearly 3.8 billion air travelers in 2016, the demand for fuel efficient and easily produced jet engines has never been higher.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] One example of AM integration with aerospace was in 2016 when Airbus delivered the first of GE's LEAP engines.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This engine has integrated 3D-printed fuel nozzles, reducing parts from 20 to 1, a 25% weight reduction, and reduced assembly times.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A fuel nozzle is the perfect inroad for additive manufacturing in a jet engine since it allows for optimized design of the complex internals and it is a low-stress, non-rotating part.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Similarly, in 2015, PW delivered their first AM parts in the PurePower PW1500G to Bombardier.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Sticking to low-stress, non-rotating parts, PW selected the compressor stators and synch ring brackets to roll out this new manufacturing technology for the first time.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] While AM is still playing a small role in the total number of parts in the jet engine manufacturing process, the return on investment can already be seen by the reduction in parts, the rapid production capabilities and the "optimized design in terms of performance and cost".
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] As technology matured, several authors began to speculate that 3D printing could aid in sustainable development in the developing world.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 2012, Filabot developed a system for closing the loop with plastic and allows for any FDM or FFF 3D printer to be able to print with a wider range of plastics.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Tentzeris demonstrated the first multi-material, vertically integrated printed electronics additive manufacturing platform (VIPRE) which enabled 3D printing of functional electronics operating up to 40 GHz.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] As the price of printers started to drop people interested in this technology had more access and freedom to make what they wanted.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] As of 2014, the price for commercial printers was still high with the cost being over $2,000.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The term "3D printing" originally referred to a process that deposits a binder material onto a powder bed with inkjet printer heads layer by layer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] More recently, the popular vernacular has started using the term to encompass a wider variety of additive-manufacturing techniques such as electron-beam additive manufacturing and selective laser melting.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The United States and global technical standards use the official term *additive manufacturing* for this broader sense.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The most commonly used 3D printing process (46% as of 2018) is a material extrusion technique called fused deposition modeling, or FDM.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] While FDM technology was invented after the other two most popular technologies, stereolithography (SLA) and selective laser sintering (SLS), FDM is typically the most inexpensive of the three by a large margin, which lends to the popularity of the process.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] As of 2020, 3D printers have reached the level of quality and price that allows most people to enter the world of 3D printing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 2020 decent quality printers can be found for less than US$200 for entry-level machines.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] These more affordable printers are usually fused deposition modeling (FDM) printers.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In November 2021 a British patient named Steve Verze received the world's first fully 3D-printed prosthetic eye from the Moorfields Eye Hospital in London.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In April 2024, the world's largest 3D printer, the Factory of the Future 1.0 was revealed at the University of Maine.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] It is able to make objects 96 feet long, or 29 meters.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In 2024, researchers used machine learning to improve the construction of synthetic bone and set a record for shock absorption.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In July 2024, researchers published a paper in *Advanced Materials Technologies* describing the development of artificial blood vessels using 3D-printing technology, which are as strong and durable as natural blood vessels.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The process involved using a rotating spindle integrated into a 3D printer to create grafts from a water-based gel, which were then coated in biodegradable polyester molecules.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In October 2025, the North Bristol NHS Trust reported that a UK cyclist named Dave Richards had received a full-face 3D-printed prosthesis, created at the newly opened Bristol 3D Medical Center at North Bristol NHS Trust.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Led by senior reconstructive scientist Amy Davey, the process used advanced scanning and medical-grade resins to replicate his facial features after severe burns.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] It marked a milestone in integrated medical 3D-printing facilities in the UK.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Additive manufacturing or 3D printing has rapidly gained importance in the field of engineering due to its many benefits.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The vision of 3D printing is design freedom, individualization, decentralization and executing processes that were previously impossible through alternative methods.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some of these benefits include enabling faster prototyping, reducing manufacturing costs, increasing product customization, and improving product quality.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Furthermore, the capabilities of 3D printing have extended beyond traditional manufacturing, like lightweight construction, or repair and maintenance with applications in prosthetics, bioprinting, food industry, rocket building, design and art and renewable energy systems.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 3D printing technology can be used to produce battery energy storage systems, which are essential for sustainable energy generation and distribution.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Another benefit of 3D printing is the technology's ability to produce complex geometries with high precision and accuracy.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This is particularly relevant in the field of microwave engineering, where 3D printing can be used to produce components with unique properties that are difficult to achieve using traditional manufacturing methods.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Additive Manufacturing processes generate minimal waste by adding material only where needed, unlike traditional methods that cut away excess material.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This reduces both material costs and environmental impact.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This reduction in waste also lowers energy consumption for material production and disposal, contributing to a smaller carbon footprint.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 3D printable models may be created with a computer-aided design (CAD) package, via a 3D scanner, or by a plain digital camera and photogrammetry software.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 3D printed models created with CAD result in relatively fewer errors than other methods.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Errors in 3D printable models can be identified and corrected before printing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 3D scanning is a process of collecting digital data on the shape and appearance of a real object, and creating a digital model based on it.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] CAD models can be saved in the stereolithography file format (STL), a de facto CAD file format for additive manufacturing that stores data based on triangulations of the surface of CAD models.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] STL is not tailored for additive manufacturing because it generates large file sizes of topology-optimized parts and lattice structures due to the large number of surfaces involved.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A newer CAD file format, the additive manufacturing file format (AMF), was introduced in 2011 to solve this problem.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] It stores information using curved triangulations.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Before printing a 3D model from an STL file, it must first be examined for errors.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A step in the STL generation known as "repair" fixes such problems in the original model.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Generally, STLs that have been produced from a model obtained through 3D scanning often have more of these errors as 3D scanning is often achieved by point to point acquisition/mapping.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 3D reconstruction often includes errors.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Once completed, the STL file needs to be processed by a piece of software called a "slicer", which converts the model into a series of thin layers and produces a G-code file containing instructions tailored to a specific type of 3D printer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] For instance FDM printers use FDM file formats.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This G-code file can then be printed with 3D printing client software (which loads the G-code and uses it to instruct the 3D printer during the 3D printing process).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Printer resolution describes layer thickness and X–Y resolution in dots per inch (dpi) or micrometers (μm).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Typical layer thickness is around 100 μm (250 DPI), although some machines can print layers as thin as 16 μm (1,600 DPI).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] X–Y resolution is comparable to that of laser printers.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] For that printer resolution, specifying a mesh resolution of 0.01–0.03 mm and a chord length ≤ 0.016 mm generates an optimal STL output file for a given model input file.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Specifying higher resolution results in larger files without increase in print quality.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Construction of a model with contemporary methods can take anywhere from several hours to several days, depending on the method used and the size and complexity of the model.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Additive systems can typically reduce this time to a few hours, although it varies widely depending on the type of machine used and the size and number of models being produced simultaneously.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Though the printer-produced resolution and surface finish are sufficient for some applications, post-processing and finishing methods allow for benefits such as greater dimensional accuracy, smoother surfaces, and other modifications such as coloration.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The surface finish of a 3D-printed part can improved using subtractive methods such as sanding and bead blasting.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] When smoothing parts that require dimensional accuracy, it is important to take into account the volume of the material being removed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some printable polymers, such as acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), allow the surface finish to be smoothed and improved using chemical vapor processes based on acetone or similar solvents.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques can benefit from annealing as a post-processing step.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Annealing a 3D-printed part allows for better internal layer bonding due to recrystallization of the part.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] It allows for an increase in mechanical properties, some of which are fracture toughness, flexural strength, impact resistance, and heat resistance.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Annealing a component may not be suitable for applications where dimensional accuracy is required, as it can introduce warpage or shrinkage due to heating and cooling.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some additively manufactured parts—especially parts that are mission critical—are post-processed with hot isostatic pressing to improve the density and to configure the microstructure to get the required mechanical performance of the printed parts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Additive or subtractive hybrid manufacturing (ASHM) is a method that involves producing a 3D printed part and using machining (subtractive manufacturing) to remove material.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Machining operations can be completed after each layer, or after the entire 3D print has been completed depending on the application requirements.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] These hybrid methods allow for 3D-printed parts to achieve better surface finishes and dimensional accuracy.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The layered structure of traditional additive manufacturing processes leads to a stair-stepping effect on part-surfaces that are curved or tilted with respect to the building platform.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The effect strongly depends on the layer height used, as well as the orientation of a part surface inside the building process.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This effect can be minimized using "variable layer heights" or "adaptive layer heights".
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] These methods decrease the layer height in places where higher quality is needed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Painting a 3D-printed part offers a range of finishes and appearances that may not be achievable through most 3D printing techniques.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The process typically involves several steps, such as surface preparation, priming, and painting.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] These steps help prepare the surface of the part and ensuring the paint adheres properly.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some additive manufacturing techniques are capable of using multiple materials simultaneously.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] These techniques are able to print in multiple colors and color combinations simultaneously and can produce parts that may not necessarily require painting.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some printing techniques require internal supports to be built to support overhanging features during construction.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] These supports must be mechanically removed or dissolved if using a water-soluble support material such as PVA after completing a print.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some commercial metal 3D printers involve cutting the metal component off the metal substrate after deposition.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A new process for the GMAW 3D printing allows for substrate surface modifications to remove aluminium or steel.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Traditionally, 3D printing focused on polymers for printing, due to the ease of manufacturing and handling polymeric materials.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] However, the method has rapidly evolved to not only print various polymers but also metals, chocolates, and ceramics, making 3D printing a versatile option for manufacturing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Layer-by-layer fabrication of three-dimensional physical models is a modern concept that "stems from the ever-growing CAD industry, more specifically the solid modeling side of CAD.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Before solid modeling was introduced in the late 1980s, three-dimensional models were created with wire frames and surfaces." but in all cases the layers of materials are controlled by the printer and the material properties.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The three-dimensional material layer is controlled by the deposition rate as set by the printer operator and stored in a computer file.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The earliest printed patented material was a hot melt type ink for printing patterns using a heated metal alloy.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Charles Hull filed the first patent on August 8, 1984, to use a UV-cured acrylic resin using a UV-masked light source at UVP Corp to build a simple model.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 was the first SL product announced by 3D Systems at Autofact Exposition, Detroit, November 1978.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The SLA-1 Beta shipped in Jan 1988 to Baxter Healthcare, Pratt and Whitney, General Motors and AMP.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The first production SLA-1 shipped to Precision Castparts in April 1988.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The UV resin material changed over quickly to an epoxy-based material resin.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] In both cases, SLA-1 models needed UV oven curing after being rinsed in a solvent cleaner to remove uncured boundary resin.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A post cure apparatus (PCA) was sold with all systems.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The early resin printers required a blade to move fresh resin over the model on each layer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The layer thickness was 0.006 inches and the HeCd laser model of the SLA-1 was 12 watts and swept across the surface at 30 inch per second.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] UVP was acquired by 3D Systems in January 1990.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A review of the history shows that a number of materials (resins, plastic powder, plastic filament and hot-melt plastic ink) were used in the 1980s for patents in the rapid prototyping field.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Masked lamp UV-cured resin was also introduced by Cubital's Itzchak Pomerantz in the Soldier 5600, Carl Deckard's (DTM) laser sintered thermoplastic powders, and adhesive-laser cut paper (LOM) stacked to form objects by Michael Feygin before 3D Systems made its first announcement.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The most common polymers for personal 3D printers are polylactic acid (PLA) and PETG.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Efforts to achieve multi-material 3D printing range from enhanced FDM-like processes like VoxelJet to novel voxel-based printing technologies like layered assembly.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A drawback of many existing 3D printing technologies is that they only allow one material to be printed at a time, limiting many potential applications that require the integration of different materials in the same object.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Multi-material 3D printing solves this problem by allowing objects of complex and heterogeneous arrangements of materials to be manufactured using a single printer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Here, a material must be specified for each voxel (or 3D printing pixel element) inside the final object volume.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The process can be fraught with complications, however, due to the isolated and monolithic algorithms.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Some commercial devices have sought to solve these issues, such as building a Spec2Fab translator, but the progress is still very limited.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Nonetheless, in the medical industry, a concept of 3D-printed pills and vaccines has been presented.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] With this new concept, multiple medications can be combined, which is expected to decrease many risks.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] With more and more applications of multi-material 3D printing, the costs of daily life and high technology development will become inevitably lower.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Metallographic materials of 3D printing is also being researched.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] By classifying each material, CIMP-3D can systematically perform 3D printing with multiple materials.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Using 3D printing and multi-material structures in additive manufacturing has allowed for the design and creation of what is called 4D printing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing is an additive manufacturing process in which the printed object changes shape with time, temperature, or some other type of stimulation.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing allows for the creation of dynamic structures with adjustable shapes, properties or functionality.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The smart/stimulus-responsive materials that are created using 4D printing can be activated to create calculated responses such as self-assembly, self-repair, multi-functionality, reconfiguration and shape-shifting.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] This allows for customized printing of shape-changing and shape-memory materials.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] 4D printing has the potential to find new applications and uses for materials (plastics, composites, metals, etc.) and has the potential to create new alloys and composites that were not viable before.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The versatility of this technology and materials can lead to advances in multiple fields of industry, including space, commercial and medical fields.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The repeatability, precision, and material range for 4D printing must increase to allow the process to become more practical throughout these industries.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] To become a viable industrial production option, there are a few challenges that 4D printing must overcome.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The challenges of 4D printing include the fact that the microstructures of these printed smart materials must be close to or better than the parts obtained through traditional machining processes.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] New and customizable materials need to be developed that have the ability to consistently respond to varying external stimuli and change to their desired shape.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] There is also a need to design new software for the various technique types of 4D printing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] The 4D printing software will need to take into consideration the base smart material, printing technique, and structural and geometric requirements of the design.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] A variety of processes, equipment, and materials are used in the production of a three-dimensional object via additive manufacturing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p01] Techniques include jetting, extrusion, additive friction stir deposition, powder bed fusion, binder jetting, stereolithography, computed axial lithography, liquid alternative, lamination, directed energy deposition, selective powder deposition, and cryogenic manufacturing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing or additive manufacturing has been used in manufacturing, medical, industry and sociocultural sectors (e.g. cultural heritage) to create successful commercial technology.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] More recently, 3D printing has also been used in the humanitarian and development sector to produce a range of medical items, prosthetics, spares and repairs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The earliest application of additive manufacturing was on the toolroom end of the manufacturing spectrum.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] For example, rapid prototyping was one of the earliest additive variants, and its mission was to reduce the lead time and cost of developing prototypes of new parts and devices, which was earlier only done with subtractive toolroom methods such as CNC milling, turning, and precision grinding.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, additive manufacturing entered production to a much greater extent.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing of food is being developed by squeezing out food, layer by layer, into three-dimensional objects.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] A large variety of foods are appropriate candidates, such as chocolate and candy, and flat foods such as crackers, pasta, and pizza.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] NASA is looking into the technology in order to create 3D-printed food to limit food waste and to make food that is designed to fit an astronaut's dietary needs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, Italian bioengineer Giuseppe Scionti developed a technology allowing the production of fibrous plant-based meat analogues using a custom 3D bioprinter, mimicking meat texture and nutritional values.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has entered the world of clothing, with fashion designers experimenting with 3D-printed bikinis, shoes, and dresses.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In commercial production, Nike used 3D printing to prototype and manufacture the 2012 Vapor Laser Talon football shoe for players of American football, and New Balance has 3D manufactured custom-fit shoes for athletes.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has come to the point where companies are printing consumer-grade eyewear with on-demand custom fit and styling (although they cannot print the lenses).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] On-demand customization of glasses is possible with rapid prototyping.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Armor-design strategies can be enhanced by taking inspiration from nature and prototyping those designs using AM.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In cars, trucks, and aircraft, additive manufacturing is beginning to transform both unibody and fuselage design and production, and powertrain design and production.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] For example, General Electric uses high-end 3D printers to build parts for turbines.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Many of these systems are used for rapid prototyping before mass production methods are employed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] AM's impact on firearms involves two dimensions: new manufacturing methods for established companies, and new possibilities for the making of do-it-yourself firearms.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2012, the US-based group Defense Distributed disclosed plans to design a working plastic 3D-printed firearm "that could be downloaded and reproduced by anybody with a 3D printer".
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] After Defense Distributed released their plans, questions were raised regarding the effects that 3D printing and widespread consumer-level CNC machining may have on gun control effectiveness.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Surgical uses of 3D printing-centric therapies began in the mid-1990s with anatomical modeling for bony reconstructive surgery planning.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Patient-matched implants were a natural extension of this work, leading to truly personalized implants that fit one unique individual.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Virtual planning of surgery and guidance using 3D printed, personalized instruments have been applied to many areas of surgery including total joint replacement and craniomaxillofacial reconstruction with great success.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] One example of this is the bioresorbable trachial splint to treat newborns with tracheobronchomalacia developed at the University of Michigan.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The use of additive manufacturing for serialized production of orthopedic implants (metals) is also increasing due to the ability to efficiently create porous surface structures that facilitate osseointegration.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The hearing aid and dental industries are expected to be the biggest areas of future development using custom 3D printing technology.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing is not just limited to inorganic materials; there have been a number of biomedical advancements made possible by 3D printing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] As of 2012, 3D bio-printing technology has been studied by biotechnology firms and academia for possible use in tissue engineering applications in which organs and body parts are built using inkjet printing techniques.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In this process, layers of living cells are deposited onto a gel medium or sugar matrix and slowly built up to form three-dimensional structures including vascular systems.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has been considered as a method of implanting stem cells capable of generating new tissues and organs in living humans.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, 3D printing technology was used for the first time to create a matrix for cell immobilization in fermentation.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Propionic acid production by *Propionibacterium acidipropionici* immobilized on 3D-printed nylon beads was chosen as a model study.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] It was shown that those 3D-printed beads were capable of promoting high-density cell attachment and propionic acid production, which could be adapted to other fermentation bioprocesses.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been employed by researchers in the pharmaceutical field.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] During the last few years, there has been a surge in academic interest regarding drug delivery with the aid of AM techniques.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] This technology offers a unique way for materials to be utilized in novel formulations.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] AM manufacturing allows for the usage of materials and compounds in the development of formulations, in ways that are not possible with conventional/traditional techniques in the pharmaceutical field, e.g. tableting, cast-molding, etc.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Moreover, one of the major advantages of 3D printing, especially in the case of fused deposition modelling (FDM), is the personalization of the dosage form that can be achieved, thus, targeting the patient's specific needs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In the not-so-distant future, 3D printers are expected to reach hospitals and pharmacies in order to provide on-demand production of personalized formulations according to the patients' needs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has also been used for medical equipment.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] During the COVID-19 pandemic 3D printers were used to supplement the strained supply of PPE through volunteers using their personally owned printers to produce various pieces of personal protective equipment (i.e. frames for face shields).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing, and open source 3D printers, in particular, are the latest technologies making inroads into the classroom.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Higher education has proven to be a major buyer of desktop and professional 3D printers which industry experts generally view as a positive indicator.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Some authors have claimed that 3D printers offer an unprecedented "revolution" in STEM education.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The evidence for such claims comes from both the low-cost ability for rapid prototyping in the classroom by students, but also the fabrication of low-cost high-quality scientific equipment from open hardware designs forming open-source labs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Additionally, Libraries around the world have also become locations to house smaller 3D printers for educational and community access.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Future applications for 3D printing might include creating open-source scientific equipment.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In the 2010s, 3D printing became intensively used in the cultural heritage field for preservation, restoration and dissemination purposes.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Many Europeans and North American Museums have purchased 3D printers and actively recreate missing pieces of their relics and archaeological monuments such as Tiwanaku in Bolivia.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The Metropolitan Museum of Art and the British Museum have started using their 3D printers to create museum souvenirs that are available in the museum shops.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Other museums, like the National Museum of Military History and Varna Historical Museum, have gone further and sell through the online platform Threeding digital models of their artifacts, created using Artec 3D scanners, in 3D printing friendly file format, which everyone can 3D print at home.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Morehshin Allahyari, an Iranian-born U.S. artist, considers her use of 3D sculpting processes of re-constructing Iranian cultural treasures as feminist activism.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Allahyari uses a 3D modeling software to reconstruct a series of cultural artifacts that were demolished by ISIS militants in 2014.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The application of 3D printing for the representation of architectural assets has many challenges.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2018, the structure of Iran National Bank was traditionally surveyed and modeled in computer graphics software (specifically, Cinema4D) and was optimized for 3D printing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The team tested the technique for the construction of the part and it was successful.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] After testing the procedure, the modellers reconstructed the structure in Cinema4D and exported the front part of the model to Netfabb.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The entrance of the building was chosen due to the 3D printing limitations and the budget of the project for producing the maquette.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing was only one of the capabilities enabled by the produced 3D model of the bank, but due to the project's limited scope, the team did not continue modelling for the virtual representation or other applications.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2021, Parsinejad et al. comprehensively compared the hand surveying method for 3D reconstruction ready for 3D printing with digital recording (adoption of photogrammetry method).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The world's first 3D-printed steel bridge was unveiled in Amsterdam in July 2021.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Spanning 12 meters over the Oudezijds Achterburgwal canal, the bridge was created using robotic arms that printed over 4,500 kilograms of stainless steel.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printed soft actuators is a growing application of 3D printing technology that has found its place in the 3D printing applications.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] These soft actuators are being developed to deal with soft structures and organs, especially in biomedical sectors and where the interaction between humans and robots is inevitable.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The majority of the existing soft actuators are fabricated by conventional methods that require manual fabrication of devices, post-processing/assembly, and lengthy iterations until the maturity of the fabrication is achieved.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Instead of the tedious and time-consuming aspects of the current fabrication processes, researchers are exploring an appropriate manufacturing approach for the effective fabrication of soft actuators.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Thus, 3D-printed soft actuators are introduced to revolutionize the design and fabrication of soft actuators with custom geometrical, functional, and control properties in a faster and inexpensive approach.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] They also enable incorporation of all actuator components into a single structure eliminating the need to use external joints, adhesives, and fasteners.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Circuit board manufacturing involves multiple steps which include imaging, drilling, plating, solder mask coating, nomenclature printing and surface finishes.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] These steps include many chemicals such as harsh solvents and acids.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing circuit boards remove the need for many of these steps while still producing complex designs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Polymer ink is used to create the layers of the build while silver polymer is used for creating the traces and holes used to allow electricity to flow.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Current circuit board manufacturing can be a tedious process depending on the design.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Specified materials are gathered and sent into inner layer processing where images are printed, developed and etched.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The etch cores are typically punched to add lamination tooling.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The cores are then prepared for lamination.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The stack-up, the buildup of a circuit board, is built and sent into lamination where the layers are bonded.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The boards are then measured and drilled.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Many steps may differ from this stage however for simple designs, the material goes through a plating process to plate the holes and surface.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The outer image is then printed, developed and etched.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] After the image is defined, the material must get coated with a solder mask for later soldering.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Nomenclature is then added so components can be identified later.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The boards are routed out of panel form into their singular or array form and then electrically tested.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Aside from the paperwork that must be completed which proves the boards meet specifications, the boards are then packed and shipped.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The benefits of 3D printing would be that the final outline is defined from the beginning, no imaging, punching or lamination is required and electrical connections are made with the silver polymer which eliminates drilling and plating.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The final paperwork would also be greatly reduced due to the lack of materials required to build the circuit board.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Complex designs which may take weeks to complete through normal processing can be 3D printed, greatly reducing manufacturing time.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2005, academic journals began to report on the possible artistic applications of 3D printing technology.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Off-the-shelf machines were increasingly capable of producing practical household applications, for example, ornamental objects.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Some practical examples include a working clock and gears printed for home woodworking machines among other purposes.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Websites associated with home 3D printing tended to include backscratchers, coat hooks, door knobs, etc.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] As of 2017, domestic 3D printing was reaching a consumer audience beyond hobbyists and enthusiasts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Several projects and companies are making efforts to develop affordable 3D printers for home desktop use.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Much of this work has been driven by and targeted at DIY/maker/enthusiast/early adopter communities, with additional ties to the academic and hacker communities.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Sped on by decreases in price and increases in quality, As of 2019 an estimated 2 million people worldwide have purchased a 3D printer for hobby use.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing has existed for decades within certain manufacturing industries where many legal regimes, including patents, industrial design rights, copyrights, and trademarks may apply.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] However, there is not much jurisprudence to say how these laws will apply if 3D printers become mainstream and individuals or hobbyist communities begin manufacturing items for personal use, for non-profit distribution, or for sale.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Any of the mentioned legal regimes may prohibit the distribution of the designs used in 3D printing or the distribution or sale of the printed item.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] To be allowed to do these things, where active intellectual property was involved, a person would have to contact the owner and ask for a licence, which may come with conditions and a price.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] However, many patent, design and copyright laws contain a standard limitation or exception for "private" or "non-commercial" use of inventions, designs or works of art protected under intellectual property (IP).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] That standard limitation or exception may leave such private, non-commercial uses outside the scope of IP rights.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Patents cover inventions including processes, machines, manufacturing, and compositions of matter and have a finite duration which varies between countries, but generally 20 years from the date of application.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Therefore, if a type of wheel is patented, printing, using, or selling such a wheel could be an infringement of the patent.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Copyright covers an expression in a tangible, fixed medium and often lasts for the life of the author plus 70 years thereafter.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] For example, a sculptor retains copyright over a statue, such that other people cannot then legally distribute designs to print an identical or similar statue without paying royalties, waiting for the copyright to expire, or working within a fair use exception.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] When a feature has both artistic (copyrightable) and functional (patentable) merits when the question has appeared in US court, the courts have often held the feature is not copyrightable unless it can be separated from the functional aspects of the item.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Attempting to restrict the distribution of gun plans via the Internet has been likened to the futility of preventing the widespread distribution of DeCSS, which enabled DVD ripping.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] After the US government had Defense Distributed take down the plans, they were still widely available via the Pirate Bay and other file sharing sites.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Downloads of the plans from the UK, Germany, Spain, and Brazil were heavy.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Some US legislators have proposed regulations on 3D printers to prevent them from being used for printing guns.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printing advocates have suggested that such regulations would be futile, could cripple the 3D printing industry and could infringe on free speech rights, with early pioneers of 3D printing professor Hod Lipson suggesting that gunpowder could be controlled instead.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Internationally, where gun controls are generally stricter than in the United States, some commentators have said the impact may be more strongly felt since alternative firearms are not as easily obtainable.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Officials in the United Kingdom have noted that producing a 3D-printed gun would be illegal under their gun control laws.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Europol stated that criminals have access to other sources of weapons but noted that as technology improves, the risks of an effect would increase.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In the United States, the FAA has anticipated a desire to use additive manufacturing techniques and has been considering how best to regulate this process.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The FAA has jurisdiction over such fabrication because all aircraft parts must be made under FAA production approval or under other FAA regulatory categories.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In December 2016, the FAA approved the production of a 3D-printed fuel nozzle for the GE LEAP engine.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Aviation attorney Jason Dickstein has suggested that additive manufacturing is merely a production method, and should be regulated like any other production method.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] He has suggested that the FAA's focus should be on guidance to explain compliance, rather than on changing the existing rules, and that existing regulations and guidance permit a company "to develop a robust quality system that adequately reflects regulatory needs for quality assurance".
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2021, first standards were issued, e.g.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] ASTM ISO/ASTM52900-21 Additive manufacturing general principles, fundamentals and vocabulary, and the above-mentioned ISO/ASTM52900-15.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2023, the ISO/ASTM 52920:2023 defined the requirements for industrial additive manufacturing processes and production sites using additive manufacturing to ensure required quality level.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Aforetime in Germany there was a draft of DIN norm issued, DIN SPEC 17071:2019.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Polymer feedstock materials can release ultrafine particles and volatile organic compounds (VOCs) if sufficiently heated, which in combination have been associated with adverse respiratory and cardiovascular health effects.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In addition, temperatures of 190 °C to 260 °C are typically reached by an FFF extrusion nozzle, which can cause skin burns.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Vat photopolymerization stereolithography printers use high-powered lasers that present a skin and eye hazard, although they are considered nonhazardous during printing because the laser is enclosed within the printing chamber.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printers also contain many moving parts that include stepper motors, pulleys, threaded rods, carriages, and small fans, which generally do not have enough power to cause serious injuries but can still trap a user's finger, long hair, or loose clothing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Most desktop FFF 3D printers do not have any added electrical safety features beyond regular internal fuses or external transformers, although the voltages in the exposed parts of 3D printers usually do not exceed 12V to 24V, which is generally considered safe.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Research on the health and safety concerns of 3D printing is new and in development due to the recent proliferation of 3D printing devices.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In 2017, the European Agency for Safety and Health at Work published a discussion paper on the processes and materials involved in 3D printing, the potential implications of this technology for occupational safety and health and avenues for controlling potential hazards.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Noise level is measured in decibels (dB), and can vary greatly in home printers from 15 dB to 75 dB.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Some main sources of noise in filament printers are fans, motors and bearings, while in resin printers the fans usually are responsible for most of the noise.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Some methods for dampening the noise from a printer may be to install vibration isolation, use larger diameter fans, perform regular maintenance and lubrication, or use a soundproofing enclosure.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing, starting with today's infancy period, requires manufacturing firms to be flexible, ever-improving users of all available technologies to remain competitive.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Advocates of additive manufacturing also predict that this arc of technological development will counter globalization, as end users will do much of their own manufacturing rather than engage in trade to buy products from other people and corporations.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The real integration of the newer additive technologies into commercial production, however, is more a matter of complementing traditional subtractive methods rather than displacing them entirely.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The futurologist Jeremy Rifkin claimed that 3D printing signals the beginning of a third industrial revolution, succeeding the production line assembly that dominated manufacturing starting in the late 19th century.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Since the 1950s, a number of writers and social commentators have speculated in some depth about the social and cultural changes that might result from the advent of commercially affordable additive manufacturing technology.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In recent years, 3D printing has created a significant impact in the humanitarian and development sector.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Its potential to facilitate distributed manufacturing is resulting in supply chain and logistics benefits, by reducing the need for transportation, warehousing and wastage.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Furthermore, social and economic development is being advanced through the creation of local production economies.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Others have suggested that as more and more 3D printers start to enter people's homes, the conventional relationship between the home and the workplace might get further eroded.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Likewise, it has also been suggested that, as it becomes easier for businesses to transmit designs for new objects around the globe, so the need for high-speed freight services might also become less.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Finally, given the ease with which certain objects can now be replicated, it remains to be seen whether changes will be made to current copyright legislation so as to protect intellectual property rights with the new technology widely available.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Some call attention to the conjunction of commons-based peer production with 3D printing and other low-cost manufacturing techniques.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The self-reinforced fantasy of a system of eternal growth can be overcome with the development of economies of scope, and here, society can play an important role contributing to the raising of the whole productive structure to a higher plateau of more sustainable and customized productivity.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Further, it is true that many issues, problems, and threats arise due to the democratization of the means of production, and especially regarding the physical ones.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] For instance, the recyclability of advanced nanomaterials is still questioned; weapons manufacturing could become easier; not to mention the implications for counterfeiting and on intellectual property.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] It might be maintained that in contrast to the industrial paradigm whose competitive dynamics were about economies of scale, commons-based peer production 3D printing could develop economies of scope.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] While the advantages of scale rest on cheap global transportation, the economies of scope share infrastructure costs (intangible and tangible productive resources), taking advantage of the capabilities of the fabrication tools.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] And following Neil Gershenfeld in that "some of the least developed parts of the world need some of the most advanced technologies", commons-based peer production and 3D printing may offer the necessary tools for thinking globally but acting locally in response to certain needs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Larry Summers wrote about the "devastating consequences" of 3D printing and other technologies (robots, artificial intelligence, etc.) for those who perform routine tasks.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In his view, "already there are more American men on disability insurance than doing production work in manufacturing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Michael Spence wrote that "Now comes a ... powerful, wave of digital technology that is replacing labor in increasingly complex tasks.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] This process of labor substitution and disintermediation has been underway for some time in service sectors—think of ATMs, online banking, enterprise resource planning, customer relationship management, mobile payment systems, and much more.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] This revolution is spreading to the production of goods, where robots and 3D printing are displacing labor." In his view, the vast majority of the cost of digital technologies comes at the start, in the design of hardware (e.g.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] 3D printers) and, more importantly, in creating the software that enables machines to carry out various tasks.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] "Once this is achieved, the marginal cost of the hardware is relatively low (and declines as scale rises), and the marginal cost of replicating the software is essentially zero.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Spence believes that, unlike prior digital technologies, which drove firms to deploy underutilized pools of valuable labor around the world, the motivating force in the current wave of digital technologies "is cost reduction via the replacement of labor".
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] For example, as the cost of 3D printing technology declines, it is "easy to imagine" that production may become "extremely" local and customized.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Moreover, production may occur in response to actual demand, not anticipated or forecast demand.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Spence believes that labor, no matter how inexpensive, will become a less important asset for growth and employment expansion, with labor-intensive, process-oriented manufacturing becoming less effective, and that re-localization will appear in both developed and developing countries.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In his view, production will not disappear, but it will be less labor-intensive, and all countries will eventually need to rebuild their growth models around digital technologies and the human capital supporting their deployment and expansion.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Spence writes that "the world we are entering is one in which the most powerful global flows will be ideas and digital capital, not goods, services, and traditional capital.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Naomi Wu regards the usage of 3D printing in the Chinese classroom (where rote memorization is standard) to teach design principles and creativity as the most exciting recent development of the technology, and more generally regards 3D printing as being the next desktop publishing revolution.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] A printer was donated to the Juan Fernandez Women's Group in 2024, to support women in the remote community to be able to create parts to fix broken equipment, without having to wait for a ship to import the needed components.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The growth of additive manufacturing could have a large impact on the environment.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Traditional subtractive manufacturing methods such as CNC milling create products by cutting away material from a larger block.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In contrast, additive manufacturing creates products layer-by layer, using the minimum required materials to create the product.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] This has the benefit of reducing material waste, which further contributes to energy savings by avoiding raw material production.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Life-cycle assessment of additive manufacturing has estimated that adopting the technology could further lower carbon dioxide emissions since 3D printing creates localized production, thus reducing the need to transport products and the emissions associated.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] AM could also allow consumers to create their own replacement parts to fix purchased products to extend the lifespan of purchased products.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] By making only the bare structural necessities of products, additive manufacturing also has the potential to make profound contributions to lightweighting.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The use of these lightweight components would allow for reductions in the energy consumption and greenhouse gas emissions of vehicles and other forms of transportation.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] A case study on an airplane component made using additive manufacturing, for example, found that the use of the component saves 63% of relevant energy and carbon dioxide emissions over the course of the product's lifetime.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] However, the adoption of additive manufacturing also has environmental disadvantages.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Firstly, AM has a high energy consumption compared to traditional processes.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] This is due to its use of processes such as lasers and high temperatures for product creation.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Secondly, despite additive manufacturing reducing up to 90% of waste compared to subtractive manufacturing, AM can generate waste that is non-recyclable.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] For example, there are issues with the recyclability of materials in metal AM as some highly regulated industries such as aerospace often insist on using virgin powder in the creation of safety critical components.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Additive manufacturing has not yet reached its theoretical material efficiency potential of 97%, but it may get closer as the technology continues to increase productivity.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Despite the drawbacks, research and industry are making further strides to support AM's sustainability.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] Some large FDM printers that melt high-density polyethylene (HDPE) pellets may also accept sufficiently clean recycled material such as chipped milk bottles.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] In addition, these printers can use shredded material from faulty builds or unsuccessful prototype versions, thus reducing overall project wastage and materials handling and storage.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] The concept has been explored in the RecycleBot.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-p02] There are also industrial efforts to produce metal powder from recycled metals.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Each process and piece of equipment has advantages and disadvantages associated with it.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] These usually involve aspects such as speed, costs, versatility with respect to feedstock, geometrical limitations and tolerances, as well as a mechanical and appearance properties of the products such as strength, texture, and color.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The variety of processes and equipment allows for numerous uses by amateurs and professionals alike.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Some lend themselves better toward industry use (in this case the term additive manufacturing is preferred) whereas others make 3D printing accessible to the average consumer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Some printers are large enough to fabricate buildings whilst others tend to micro and nanoscale sized objects and in general many different technologies can be exploited to physically produce the designed objects.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Inkjet printing was pioneered by Teletype which introduced the electrostatic pull Inktronic teleprinter in 1966.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The printer had 40 jets that offered a break-through speed of 120 characters per second.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Continuous inkjets were popular in the 1950–1960's before Drop-On-Demand inkjets were invented in 1972.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Continuous three-dimensional inks were wax based and low temperature metal alloys.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Printing with these hot-melt inks produced alpha-numeric characters that were solid and raised, but no one recognized them as 3D printing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] In 1971, a young engineer, Johannes Gottwald patented a liquid metal recorder that printed large characters in metal for signage, but Teletype Corp ignored the discovery.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Braille was printed with wax inks but never commercialized in the 1960s.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Research researched printing from 1982 -1983 and decided that single-nozzle inkjet was a possible fit.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] He recruited engineers Al Hock, Tom Peer, Dave Lutz, Jim and Kathy McMahon to join the company, which became Howtek, Inc.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The company's Pixelmaster device used Tefzel nozzles, which allowed the inkjet to work at high temperature and support thermoplastic hot-melt inks.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The device could handle a frequency range of 1–16,000 drops per second.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] It featured 32 inkjet single nozzles per printhead, printing 4 colors (8 jets per color) CMYK.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The printhead rotated at 121 rpm and placed uniform drops precisely as subtractive printing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] This technology of hot-melt inks printing layers of CMYK was a precursor to a 3D patent by Richard Helinski.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Chuck Hull patented stereolithography (SLA) in 1986.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] In 1993, Helinski's patent was licensed first by Sanders Prototype, Inc.,(later Solidscape, Inc) manufacturer of the first desktop rapid prototype printer, the Modelmaker 6 Pro.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] It used Howtek style inkjets and thermoplastic inks.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Models printed with thermoplastic were perfect for investment casting with no ash during burnout.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Thermoplastic ink drop printing is accurate and precise enough for jewelers and detail sensitive CAD designers.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The Howtek inkjets that were designed to print a page in 4 minutes were employed to print for as long as 4 days straight.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Several 3D printing processes have been invented since the late 1970s.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The printers were originally large, expensive, and highly limited in what they could produce.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] A large number of additive processes are now available.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The main differences between processes are in the way layers are deposited to create parts and in the materials that are used.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] With laminated object manufacturing (LOM), thin layers are cut to shape and joined (e.g., paper, polymer, metal).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Particle deposition using inkjet technology prints layers of material in the form of individual drops.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Each drop of solid ink from hot-melt material actually prints one particle or one object.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Color hot-melt inks print individual drops of CMYK on top of each other to produce a single color object with 1–3 layers melted together.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Complex 3D models are printed with many overlapping drops fused together into layers as defined by the sliced CAD file.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Inkjet technology allows 3D models to be solid or open cell structures as defined by the 3D printer inkjet print configuration.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Each method has its own advantages and drawbacks, which is why some companies offer a choice of powder and polymer for the material used to build the object.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Others sometimes use standard, off-the-shelf business paper as the build material to produce a durable prototype.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The main considerations in choosing a machine are generally speed, costs of the 3D printer, of the printed prototype, choice and cost of the materials, and color capabilities.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Printers that work directly with metals are generally expensive.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] However less expensive printers can be used to make a mold, which is then used to make metal parts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] In material jetting a nozzle is drawn across an absorbent surface.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The material is either wicked, electrostatically pulled from a larger jet, pressurized to expel material either continuously, or in short bursts as spray or drops.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Nozzles can be single nozzle with one fluid chamber or multi-nozzle with single or multi-fluid chambers, or combinations of these.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The material needs to have low enough viscosity to pass through the nozzle opening.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Hot-melt materials can be melted to become liquid.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The inks must be thick enough to accumulate vertically.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Continuous inkjet technology (CIT) began by printing signs and documents on paper, later adapted to print metals.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Wax and thermoplastics were the first 3D materials, printed by drop-on-demand (DOD) inkjets.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Binder jetting deposits binding adhesive onto layers of powdered material.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Also known as inkjet 3D printing, the process spreads powder (ceramic, metal, or plastic-based, including plaster and resins) across a platform.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] A print head deposits binder in the cross-section of each layer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Modern printers cure (solidify) the binder at each layer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The resulting part is further cured in an oven to remove most binder.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Operators sinter it in a kiln following a material-specific time-temperature curve.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Unbound powder supports overhangs during printing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The method enables full-color prototypes and elastomer parts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Strength improves by impregnating voids with wax, thermoset polymer, bronze, or other compatible materials.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Fused filament fabrication (FFF), trademarked as fused deposition modeling (FDM), extrudes thermoplastic material to build objects layer by layer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] As of 2023, FDM was the dominant 3D printing method.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] A filament of thermoplastic feeds into an extrusion nozzle.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The nozzle head heats the material to its melting point and extrudes it onto a build platform.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Stepper or servomotors move the head and control flow along three axes.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Computer-aided manufacturing software generates G-code.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Common materials include acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), polycarbonate (PC), polylactic acid (PLA), high-density polyethylene (HDPE), PC/ABS, polyphenylsulfone (PPSU), and high impact polystyrene (HIPS).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Open-source projects recycle post-consumer plastic waste into filament using shredders and extruders like recyclebots.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] PTFE tubing transfers filament due to high-temperature resistance.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Variants use pellets or particles instead of filament, known as fused pellet/particle/granular fabrication (FPF/FGF), aiding the use of recycled materials.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Metal wire enables printing via wire arc additive manufacturing (WAAM), reducing costs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Molten glass deposition creates artistic works.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Use of FDM limits complex geometries such as overhangs or stalactite structures.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Slicer software adds removable support structures for such features.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Scott Crump developed the process in the late 1980s.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] It evolved from automated polymeric foil hot air welding, hot-melt gluing, and gasket deposition.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] After patent expiration, open-source RepRap projects fostered community development and DIY variants.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Additive friction stir deposition (AFSD) is a solid-state metal additive manufacturing process that uses a rotating tool to deposit feedstock material onto a substrate.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] AFSD offers a number of advantages over other metal additive manufacturing processes, including high material utilization, low energy consumption, and the ability to print metal alloys incompatible with melt-based processes.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Powder bed fusion (PBF) selectively fuses material in a granular bed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The process fuses layer parts, raises the working area, adds granules, and repeats until completion.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Unfused powder supports overhangs and thin walls, reducing auxiliary supports.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] PBF includes direct metal laser sintering (DMLS), selective laser sintering (SLS), selective laser melting (SLM), multi-jet fusion (MJF), and electron beam melting (EBM).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] These methods handle diverse materials and enable complex geometries.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Selective laser sintering (SLS) uses polymers and metals (e.g., PA, PA-GF, PEEK, alumide, carbonmide, elastomers) and direct metal laser sintering (DMLS).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Deckard and Joseph Beaman developed and patented it in the mid-1980s under DARPA sponsorship.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Housholder patented a similar, uncommercialized process in 1979.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Selective laser melting (SLM) does not use sintering for the fusion of powder granules but melts the powder using a high-energy laser to create fully dense materials in a layer-wise method that has mechanical properties similar to those of conventional manufactured metals.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Electron beam melting (EBM) melts metal powder (e.g., titanium alloys) layer by layer with an electron beam in high vacuum, producing void-free parts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Multi-jet fusion (MJF) combines fusing and detailing agents with an inkjet array that it heats to solidify layers without lasers.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Binder jetting spreads powder (plaster or resins) and prints binder via inkjet.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Selective heat sintering applies heat with a thermal printhead to thermoplastic powder, offering a cheaper, scalable alternative.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Another 3D printing approach is the selective fusing of materials in a granular bed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The technique fuses parts of the layer and then moves up, adding layers of granules and repeating the process until the piece is complete.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] This process uses the unfused media to support overhangs and thin walls, which reduces the need for auxiliary supports.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Vat photopolymerization cures liquid photopolymer resin layer by layer using light sources such as lasers, digital light projectors (DLP), or LEDs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The process exposes resin in a vat to controlled light under safelight conditions.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Photopolymerization cross-links monomers, typically via carbon-carbon double bonds in acrylates, when exposed to chromophores or photosensitive additives.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Excess liquid resin drains after completion.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Objet PolyJet systems spray photopolymer in ultra-thin layers (16–30 μm).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] UV light cures each layer immediately, enabling instant handling without a later curing step.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Gel-like supports are removed by hand or water jetting.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The method suits elastomers and ophthalmic lenses.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Multiphoton polymerization uses focused lasers to cure gel only at focal points due to nonlinear photoexcitation.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] This enables features under 100 nm and complex moving structures.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Mask-image-projection stereolithography slices models into planes, converts slices to masks, and projects them onto resin to cure layers.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Some systems support multiple materials.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Continuous liquid interface production (CLIP) uses an oxygen-permeable window below the resin pool to create a persistent liquid "dead zone." This enables continuous extraction of the object, reducing times from hours to minutes.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Dynamic Interface Printing (DIP) submerges a hollow print head with a transparent window into prepolymer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Visible light cures at the air-liquid meniscus.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Air pressure and acoustic modulation control the interface for precision and material flow.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Preceramic polymers enable ceramic printing (e.g., silicon carbide) via photopolymerization.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Some systems solidify synthetic resin with LEDs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Powder-fed directed-energy deposition melts supplied metal powder with a laser, a localized analog of selective laser sintering.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Vat photopolymerization is widely used for 3D printing of ceramic materials such as alumina and zirconia.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Preceramic polymers also enable ceramic printing (e.g., silicon carbide) via photopolymerization.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The precision of ceramic vat photopolymerization is often challenged by light scattering and lateral overcure, which can obstruct fine internal features.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Recent research has established quantitative frameworks for printing "vascular ceramics" with embedded internal channels.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] By optimizing cure depth-to-layer height ratios and applying geometric pre-compensation to account for symmetric tapering, fully enclosed channels can be achieved.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Computed axial lithography reverses the principle of computed tomography (CT) to create prints in photo-curable resin.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] It was developed by a collaboration between the University of California, Berkeley with Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] It creates objects using a series of 2D images projected onto a cylinder of resin.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] It is notable for its ability to build objects more quickly than other resin methods and can embed objects within the prints.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Liquid additive manufacturing (LAM) is an additive manufacturing technique which deposits a liquid or highly viscous material (e.g.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Liquid Silicone Rubber) onto a build surface to create an object, which is then vulcanised using heat to harden it.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The process was created by Adrian Bowyer and extended by German company RepRap.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Programmable tooling involves creating a temporary mold, which is then filled via a conventional injection molding process and then immediately dissolved.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] In some printers, paper can be used as the build material, lowering costs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] These printers that cut cross-sections out of special adhesive coated paper using a carbon dioxide laser and laminates them.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Alternatively, ordinary sheets of office paper can be cut by a tungsten carbide blade, followed by selective deposition of adhesive and pressure to bond layers.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Other printers print laminated objects using plastic and metal sheets.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Ultrasonic consolidation (UC) or ultrasonic additive manufacturing (UAM) is a low temperature additive technique for metals.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] A high-power laser melts metal powder supplied to the focus of the laser beam.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The laser beam typically travels through the center of the deposition head and is lens-focused to a small spot.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The build occurs on an X-Y table which is driven by a tool path created from a digital model.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The deposition head is moved vertically as each layer is completed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Some systems make use of 5-axis or 6-axis systems (*i.e.* articulated arms) capable of delivering material on the substrate (a printing bed, or a pre-existing part) with few to no spatial access restrictions.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Metal powder is delivered and distributed around the head or can be split by an internal manifold and delivered through nozzles arranged around the deposition head.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] A hermetically sealed chamber filled with inert gas or a local inert shroud gas (sometimes combined) are often used to shield the melt pool from atmospheric oxygen, to limit oxidation and better control material properties.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The powder-fed directed-energy process is similar to selective laser sintering, but the metal powder is projected only where material is to be added to the part at that moment.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The laser heats and creates a "melt pool" on the substrate, in which the new powder is injected quasi-simultaneously.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The process supports materials including titanium, stainless steel, aluminum, tungsten, and other specialty materials as well as composites and functionally graded material.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The process can build new metal parts, but can also add material to existing parts, supporting coatings, repair, and hybrid manufacturing applications.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] LENS (Laser Engineered Net Shaping), is one example.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Laser-based wire-feed systems, such as laser metal deposition-wire (LMD-w), feed wire through a nozzle that is melted by a laser using inert gas shielding in either an open environment (gas surrounding the laser), or in a sealed chamber.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Electron beam freeform fabrication uses an electron beam heat source inside a vacuum chamber.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] It is also possible to use conventional gas metal arc welding attached to a 3D stage to 3-D print metals such as steel, bronze and aluminum.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Low-cost open source RepRap-style 3-D printers have been outfitted with Arduino-based sensors and demonstrated reasonable metallurgical properties from conventional welding wire as feedstock.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] In selective powder deposition (SPD), build and support powders are selectively deposited into a crucible, such that the build powder takes the shape of the desired object and support powder fills the rest of the crucible.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Then an infill material is applied, such that it comes in contact with the build powder.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Then the crucible is fired in a kiln between the melting point of the infill and the powders.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] When the infill melts, it soaks the build powder.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] But it doesn't soak the support powder, because the support powder is chosen to not be wettable by the infill.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] If at the firing temperature, the atoms of the infill material and the build powder are mutually defusable, such as with copper powder and zinc infill, then the resulting material is a uniform mixture of those atoms, in this case, bronze.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] But if the atoms are not mutually defusable, such as tungsten and copper at 1100°C, then the resulting material is a composite.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] To prevent shape distortion, the firing temperature must be below the solidus temperature of the resulting alloy.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Cryogenic 3D printing is a collection of techniques that forms solid structures by freezing liquid materials as they are deposited.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] As each liquid layer is applied, it is cooled by the low temperature of the previous layer and printing environment which solidifies it.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Cryogenic techniques requires a controlled printing environment.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The ambient temperature must be below the material's freezing point to ensure the structure remains solid during manufacturing and the humidity must remain low to prevent frost formation between layers.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Materials typically include water and water-based solutions, such as brine, slurry, and hydrogels.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Cryogenic techniques include rapid freezing prototype (RFP), low-temperature deposition manufacturing (LDM), and freeze-form extrusion fabrication (FEF).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Electrochemical additive manufacturing (ECAM) is as a cluster of technologies with the potential to fabricate 3D micro/nanostructures within diverse materials.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] ECAM technologies include localized electrochemical deposition (LED), meniscus-confined electrodeposition (MCED), electrohydrodynamic redox printing (EHD-RP), fluid FM electrodeposition, and scanning ion conductance microscopy (SICM).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The electrolyte of a target metal is placed inside a glass capillary pipette.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] An electronic-ionic circuit is formed by a liquid capillary created between the pipette's tip and the conductive substrate.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Metal ions reduce (release oxygen) when a voltage is applied and deposit on the substrate.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Precision positioners control the pipette in three dimensions, creating the necessary three-dimensional objects.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Manufacturing happens at nearl room temperature and produces fewer thermal defects.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] It permits feature resolutions in the 30-50 micrometer range.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] ECAM is under consideration as a technique for manufacturing advanced copper cooling plates for data centers that provide 98% reductions in energy consumption for cooling.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] As of October 2012, additive manufacturing systems ranged from $2,000 to $500,000 in price and were employed in industries including aerospace, architecture, automotive, defense, and medical replacements.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] These devices are used for prototyping, jig making, fixturing, fixing small custom components, and complete products.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Higher end 3-D printers have now become relatively common for production and additive manufacturing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] For example, General Electric uses additive manufacturing to build turbine parts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Rapid prototyping saves time and reduces complexity.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Volkswagen uses 3D printers to print tooling, jigs and fixtures.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] As of 2018 they estimated that 3D printers save €250,000 per year in costs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] One 2018 report estimated that almost 75% of desktop 3D printers made are used in industry.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Military and defense systems also incorporating the use of 3D printers.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The Royal Netherlands Air Force is using desktop 3D printers to make fixtures and alignment tools.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Hill Air Force Base uses 3D printed parts to replace jet parts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Higher education is a major buyer of desktop and professional 3D printers.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] In higher education, 3D printing is used to fabricate equipment.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] For example, chemists can 3D print flow reactor systems that would otherwise exceed typical budgets, such as a device created at the UCL School of Pharmacy in the UK.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Many libraries house smaller 3D printers for educational and community access.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] DIY/Maker/enthusiast/early adopter communities, with ties to the academic and hacker communities, led consumer-level adoption.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] RepRap Project is one of the longest running desktop projects.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] It aims to produce a free and open source hardware (FOSH) 3D printer, under the GNU General Public License that is capable of replicating itself by printing many of its own parts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] RepRaps can print circuit boards and metal parts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] As of 2016, the most popular 3D printer was the Prusa i3, a RepRap printer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Many related projects have used RepRap for inspiration, creating an ecosystem of related or derivative 3D printers, most of which are also open-source.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Development of open source 3D printers enables greater customization and the use of public domain designs to fabricate open source appropriate technology.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The cost of 3D printers decreased dramatically after about 2010, with machines that used to cost $20,000 falling below $1,000.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The open source Fab@Home project has developed printers for general use with anything that can be squirted through a nozzle, from chocolate to silicone sealant and chemical reactants.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] In addition, several RecycleBots such as the commercialized Filastruder have been designed and fabricated to convert waste plastic, such as shampoo containers and milk jugs, into inexpensive RepRap filament.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Larger 3D printers have been developed for industrial, education, and demonstrative uses.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Another type of large printer is big area additive manufacturing (BAAM).
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] The goal is to develop printers that can produce a large object in high speed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Another BAAM machine developed by Lockheed Martin aims to print objects up to 100 feet (30 m) long to be used in aerospace industries.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Microelectronic device fabrication methods can be employed to print nanoscale objects.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Such printed objects are typically grown on a substrate, e.g., a silicon wafer, to which they adhere after printing as they are too small and fragile to be manipulated post-deposition.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] In one technique, 3D nanostructures are printed by moving a dynamic stencil mask during the deposition process, somewhat analogous to the extrusion method of traditional 3D printers.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Programmable-height nanostructures with resolutions as small as 10 nm have been produced in this fashion, by metallic physical vapor deposition using a mechanical piezo-actuator controlled stencil mask having a milled nanopore in a silicon nitride membrane.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Another method enhances the photopolymerization process on a much smaller scale, using finely-focused lasers controlled by adjustable mirrors.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] This method produced objects with feature resolutions of 100 nm as of 2013.
[src:additive-manufacturing/3d-printing-processes] Onr micron -wide, millimetre-long copper wires have been printed using lasers.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] Selective laser sintering (SLS) was developed and patented by Dr.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] Joe Beaman at the University of Texas at Austin in the mid-1980s, under sponsorship of DARPA.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] Deckard and Beaman were involved in the resulting start up company Desk Top Manufacturing (DTM) Corp, established to design and build the SLS machines.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] In 2001, 3D Systems, the biggest competitor to DTM Corp. and SLS technology, acquired DTM Corp..
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] The most recent patent regarding Deckard's SLS technology was issued January 28, 1997 and expired January 28, 2014.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] A similar process was patented without being commercialized by R.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] As SLS requires the use of high-powered lasers it is often too expensive, not to mention possibly too dangerous, to use in the home.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] An additive manufacturing layer technology, SLS involves the use of a high power laser (for example, a carbon dioxide laser) to fuse small particles of plastic, metal, ceramic, or glass powders into a mass that has a desired three-dimensional shape.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] The laser selectively fuses powdered material by scanning cross-sections generated from a 3-D digital description of the part (for example from a CAD file or scan data) on the surface of a powder bed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] After each cross-section is scanned, the powder bed is lowered by one layer thickness, a new layer of material is applied on top, and the process is repeated until the part is completed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] Because finished part density depends on peak laser power, rather than laser duration, a SLS machine typically uses a pulsed laser.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] The SLS machine preheats the bulk powder material in the powder bed somewhat below its melting point, to make it easier for the laser to raise the temperature of the selected regions the rest of the way to the melting point.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] In contrast with SLA and FDM, which most often require special support structures to fabricate overhanging designs, SLS does not need extra material or special considerations for support structures because the part being constructed is surrounded by unsintered powder at all times.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] This allows for the construction of previously impossible geometries.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] Since the machine's chamber is always filled with powder material, "*Nesting*" can be used to save time and cost by printing multiple parts at once.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] While SLA and FDM prints can contain parts that are hollow yet fully enclosed, SLS requires hollow enclosures to have an opening for the unsintered powder within to be drained.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] The quality of printed structures depends on the various factors include powder properties such as particle size and shape, density, roughness, and porosity.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] Furthermore, the particle distribution and their thermal properties have a significant effect on the flowability of the powder.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] Commercially-available materials used in SLS come in powder form and include, but are not limited to, polymers such as polyamides (PA), polystyrenes (PS), thermoplastic elastomers (TPE), and polyaryletherketones (PAEK).
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] Polyamides are the most commonly used SLS materials due to their ideal sintering behavior as a semi-crystalline thermoplastic, resulting in parts with desirable mechanical properties.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] Metal materials are not commonly used in SLS since the development of selective laser melting.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] The process can result in spherical or irregular shaped particles as low as five microns in diameter.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] Powder particle size distributions are typically gaussian and range from 15 to 100 microns in diameter, although this can be customized to suit different layer thicknesses in the SLS process.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] Chemical binder coatings can be applied to the powder surfaces post-process; these coatings aid in the sintering process and are especially helpful to form composite material parts such as with alumina particles coated with thermoset epoxy resin.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] Sintering in SLS primarily occurs in the liquid state when the powder particles forms a micro-melt layer at the surface, resulting in a reduction in viscosity and the formation of a concave radial bridge between particles, known as necking, due to the material's response to lower its surface energy.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] In the case of coated powders, the purpose of the laser is to melt the surface coating which will act as a binder.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] Solid state sintering is also a contributing factor, albeit with a much reduced influence, and occurs at temperatures below the melting temperature of the material.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] The principal driving force behind the process is again the material's response to lower its free energy state resulting in diffusion of molecules across particles.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] SLS technology is in wide use at many industries around the world due to its ability to easily make complex geometries with little to no added manufacturing effort.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] Its most common application is in prototype parts early in the design cycle such as for investment casting patterns, automotive hardware, and wind tunnel models.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] SLS is also increasingly being used in limited-run manufacturing to produce end-use parts for aerospace, military, medical, pharmaceutical, and electronics hardware.
[src:additive-manufacturing/direct-metal-laser-sintering] On a shop floor, SLS can be used for rapid manufacturing of tooling, jigs, and fixtures.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Fused filament printing has in the 2010s–2020s been the most popular process (by number of machines) for hobbyist-grade 3D printing because of its relatively low cost and ease of use.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Other techniques such as photopolymerisation and powder sintering may offer better results, but they are much more costly.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The 3D printer head or 3D printer extruder is a part in material extrusion additive manufacturing responsible for raw material melting or softening and forming it into a continuous profile.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Fused deposition modeling was developed by S.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Scott Crump, co-founder of Stratasys, in 1988.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The patent on FDM technology expired in 2009, so people could use this type of printing without asking or paying Stratasys for the right to do so.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Soon after, a large industry of commercial FFF-based 3D printers could flourish.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Additionally, there would be a litany of DIY and open-source 3D printer designs popular with amateurs and institutions, including designs produced by RepRap.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The expiry of the patent has been credited for enabling a two-orders-of-magnitude price drop since this technology's creation.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] As with Chevron's Techron, Stratasys still owns the trademark on the term "FDM," leading to the adoption of the alternative name FFF by RepRap and others.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] 3D printing, also referred to as additive manufacturing (AM), involves manufacturing a part by depositing material layer by layer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] There is a wide array of different AM technologies that can do this, including material extrusion, binder jetting, material jetting and directed energy deposition.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] These processes have varied types of extruders and extrude different materials to achieve the final product.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Fused filament fabrication uses material extrusion to print items, where a feedstock material is pushed through an extruder.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] In most fused filament fabrication 3D printing machines, the feedstock material comes in the form of a **filament** wound onto a spool.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The 3D printer liquefier is the component predominantly used in this type of printing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Extruders for these printers have a cold end and a hot end.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The cold end pulls material from the spool, using gear- or roller-based torque to the material and controlling the feed rate by means of a stepper motor.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The cold end pushes feedstock into the hot end.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The hot end consists of a heating chamber and a nozzle.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The heating chamber hosts the liquefier, which melts the feedstock to transform it into a liquid.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] It allows the molten material to exit from the small nozzle to form a thin, tacky bead of plastic that will adhere to the material it is laid on.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The nozzle will usually have a diameter of between 0.3 mm and 1.0 mm.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Different types of nozzles and heating methods are used depending upon the material to be printed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Brass nozzles are sufficient for soft plastics like PLA, while hardened steel nozzles are needed for more abrasive and tougher materials or plastics with additives (like for example PLA with added wood or carbon fiber).
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Different types of nozzles have different ways of replacing them.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The most common used nozzles are the V6 nozzles made popular by E3D and MK8 nozzles, which both have standard M6×1 metric threads.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Changing the nozzle must be done while hot, to avoid plastic leaks.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The nozzle can be moved in both horizontal and vertical directions, and is mounted to a mechanical stage, which can be moved in the **xy** plane.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] As the nozzle is moved over the table in a prescribed geometry, it deposits a thin bead of extruded plastic, called a *road* which solidifies quickly upon contact with the substrate and/or roads deposited earlier.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Solid layers are generated by following a rasterizing motion where the roads are deposited side by side within an enveloping domain boundary.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Stepper motors or servo motors are typically employed to move the extrusion head.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The mechanism used is often an X-Y-Z rectilinear design, although other mechanical designs such as deltabot have been employed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Once a layer is completed, the platform is lowered (or the extruder is raised) in the **z direction** in order to start the next layer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] This process continues until the fabrication of the object is completed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] For successful bonding of the roads in the process, thermal control of the deposited material is necessary.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The system can be kept inside a chamber, maintained at a temperature below the melting point of the material being deposited.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Although as a printing technology FFF is very flexible, and it is capable of dealing with small overhangs by the support from lower layers, FFF generally has some restrictions on the slope of the overhang, and cannot produce unsupported stalactites.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Myriad materials are available, such as acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), polylactic acid (PLA), polycarbonate (PC), polyamide (PA), polystyrene (PS), lignin, rubber, among many others, with different trade-offs between strength and temperature properties.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] In addition, even the color of a given thermoplastic material may affect the strength of the printed object.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] During FFF, the hot molten polymer is exposed to air.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Operating the FFF process within an inert gas atmosphere such as nitrogen or argon can significantly increase the layer adhesion and leads to improved mechanical properties of the 3D printed objects.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] An inert gas is routinely used to prevent oxidation during selective laser sintering.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] During extrusion the thermoplastic filament is introduced by mechanical pressure from rollers, into the liquefier (or hotend), where it melts and is then extruded.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Flow geometry of the extruder, heating method and the melt flow behavior of a non-Newtonian fluid are of main consideration in the part.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The rollers are the only drive mechanism in the material delivery system, therefore filament is under tensile stress upstream to the roller and under compression at the downstream side acting as a plunger.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Therefore, compressive stress is the driving force behind the extrusion process.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The force required to extrude the melt must be sufficient to overcome the pressure drop across the system, which strictly depends on the viscous properties of the melted material and the flow geometry of the liquefier and nozzle.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The melted material is subjected to shear deformation during the flow.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Shear thinning behavior is observed in most of the materials used in this type of 3-D printing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] This is modeled using power law for generalized Newtonian fluids.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The temperature is regulated by heat input from electrical coil heaters.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The system continuously adjusts the power supplied to the coils according to the temperature difference between the desired value and the value detected by the thermocouple, forming a negative feedback loop.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] This is similar to ambient heating of a room.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] FFF and the other technologies of additive manufacturing by material extrusion (EAM) techniques are commonly used for prototyping and rapid manufacturing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Rapid prototyping facilitates iterative testing, and for very short runs, rapid manufacturing can be a relatively inexpensive alternative.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] EAM is also used in prototyping scaffolds for medical tissue engineering applications.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Moreover, EAM with multi extrusion have become very popular to fabricate biomimetic composites.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] FFF is also applied in manufacturing within other sectors, including aerospace, automotive, construction, electronics, energy, pharmaceuticals, sports, textiles, and toys.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] There are multiple projects in the open-sourced community aimed at processing post-consumer plastic waste into filament.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] These involve machines used to shred and extrude the plastic material into filament such as recyclebots.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Much of this work has been driven by and targeted at DIY/enthusiast/early adopter communities, with additional ties to the academic and hacker communities.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] RepRap is one of the longest running projects in the desktop category.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The RepRap project aims to produce a free and open source hardware (FOSH) 3D printer, whose full specifications are released under the GNU General Public License, and which is capable of replicating itself by printing many of its own (plastic) parts to create more machines.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] RepRaps have already been shown to be able to print circuit boards and metal parts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Fab@Home is the other opensource hardware project for DIY 3D printers.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Because of the FOSH aims of RepRap, many related projects have used their design for inspiration, creating an ecosystem of related or derivative 3D printers, most of which are also open source designs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The availability of these open source designs means that variants of 3D printers are easy to invent.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The quality and complexity of printer designs, however, as well as the quality of kit or finished products, varies greatly from project to project.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] This rapid development of open source 3D printers is gaining interest in many spheres as it enables hyper-customization and the use of public domain designs to fabricate open source appropriate technology.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] This technology can also assist initiatives in sustainable development since technologies are easily and economically made from resources available to local communities.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Customer-driven product customization and demand for cost and time savings have increased interest in agility of manufacturing process.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] This has led to improvements in rapid prototyping technologies.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The development of extruders is going rapidly because of the open source 3-D printer movement caused by products like RepRap.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] E3D and BondTech are the most known extruder manufacturers currently on the market.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Consistent improvements are seen in the form of increased heating temperature of liquefiers, better control and precision of prints, and improved support for a wide variety of materials.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Besides the improved hardware, the ability to calibrate the extruder according to the hardware setup has come a long way.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The cost of 3D printers has decreased dramatically since about 2010, with machines that used to cost US$20,000 now costing less than US$1,000.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] For instance, as of 2017, several companies and individuals are selling parts to build various RepRap designs, with prices starting at about £99 / US$100.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The open source Fab@Home project has developed printers for general use with anything that can be extruded through a nozzle, from chocolate to silicone sealant and chemical reactants.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Printers following the project's designs have been available from suppliers in kits or in pre-assembled form since 2012 at prices in the US$2,000 range.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The LulzBot 3D printers manufactured by Aleph Objects are another example of an open-source application of fused deposition modeling technology.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The flagship model in the LulzBot line, the TAZ printer takes inspiration for its design from the RepRap Mendel90 and Prusa i3 models.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The LulzBot 3D printer is currently the only printer on the market to have received the "Respects Your Freedom" certification from the Free Software Foundation.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] As of September 2018 RepRap style printers are readily available in kit form through online retailers.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] These kits come complete with all parts needed to make a functioning printer, often including electronic files for test printing as well as a small quantity of PLA filament.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Filaments used for printing with FFF printers are also substantially more cost-effective than their SLA resin counterparts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] If we use 3DBenchy as a benchmark for comparing both technologies, it would cost roughly $0.20 to print such a model with an FFF machine, whereas the same object would cost almost $1.00 if created with resin.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Plastic is the most common material for 3d printing via FFF and other EAM variants.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Various polymers may be used, including acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), polycarbonate (PC), polylactic acid (PLA), high-density polyethylene (HDPE), PC/ABS, polyethylene terephthalate (PETG), polyphenylsulfone (PPSU) and high impact polystyrene (HIPS).
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] In general, the polymer is in the form of a filament fabricated from virgin resins.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Additionally, fluoropolymers such as PTFE tubing are used in the process due to the material's ability to withstand high temperatures.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] This ability is especially useful in transferring filaments.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The many different variants of EAM, i.e. of material Extrusion based Additive Manufacturing allow dealing with many additional material types, summarised in the table below.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The majority of fused filament printers follow the same basic design.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] A flat bed is used as the starting point for the print workpiece.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] A gantry above this carries the moving print head.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The gantry design is optimized for movement mostly in the horizontal X & Y directions, with a slow climb in the Z direction as the piece is printed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Stepper motors drive the movement through either leadscrews or toothed belt drives.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] It is common, owing to the differences in movement speed, to use toothed belts for the X, Y drives and a leadscrew for Z.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Some machines also have X axis movement on the gantry, but move the bed (and print job) for Y.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] As, unlike laser cutters, head movement speeds are low, stepper motors are universally used and there is no need to use servomotors instead.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Many printers, originally those influenced by the RepRap project, make extensive use of 3D printed components in their own construction.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] These are typically printed connector blocks with a variety of angled holes, joined by cheap steel threaded rod.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] This makes a construction that is cheap and easy to assemble, easily allows non-perpendicular framing joints, but does require access to a 3D printer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The notion of 'bootstrapping' 3D printers like this has been something of a dogmatic theme within the RepRap designs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The lack of stiffness in the rod also requires either triangulation, or gives the risk of a gantry structure that flexes and vibrates in service, reducing print quality.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Many machines, especially commercial machines such as the Bambu X1, Ultimaker S Series and Creality K2, now use box-like semi-enclosed frames of either laser-cut plywood, plastic, pressed steel sheet and more recently aluminum extrusions.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] These are cheap, rigid and can also be used as the basis for an enclosed print volume, allowing temperature control within it to control warping of the print job.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] A handful of machines use polar coordinates instead, usually machines optimized to print objects with circular symmetry.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] These have a radial gantry movement and a rotating bed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Although there are some potential mechanical advantages to this design for printing hollow cylinders, their different geometry and the resulting non-mainstream approach to print planning still keeps them from being popular as yet.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Although it is an easy task for a robot's motion planning to convert from Cartesian to polar coordinates, gaining any advantage from this design also requires the print slicing algorithms to be aware of the rotational symmetry from the outset.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The ways extruders are mounted on the rest of the machine have evolved over time into informal mounting standards.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Such factor standards allow new extruder designs to be tested on existing printer frames, and new printer frame designs to use existing extruders.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] A different approach is taken with 'Rostock' or 'Kossel' pattern printers, based on a delta robot mechanism.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] These have a large open print volume with a three-armed delta robot mounted at the top.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] This design of robot is noted for its low inertia and ability for fast movement over a large volume.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Stability and freedom from vibration when moving a heavy print head on the end of spindly arms is a technical challenge though.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] This design has mostly been favored as a means of gaining a large print volume without a large and heavy gantry.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] As the print head moves, the distance of its filament from storage coil to head also changes; the tension created on the filament is another technical challenge to overcome to avoid affecting the print quality.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Most printers are designed to function optimally at room temperature (approximately 18–25 °C) and preferably with as low humidity as possible, and during printing it is important that the temperature and humidity remain stable and that drafts are avoided to prevent the plastic from warping.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] For example, PLA should be printed at room temperature (18-25 celsius), while ABS should have a consistent chamber temperature of around 60-70 celsius.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] If the printer is to be placed in a chamber, it is important that the printer is designed for such use, for example by having electronics with active cooling, to reduce the risk of fire.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Filament printers may have negative effects on health and safety due to dust and harmful emissions, but little research has been published.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] 3D printers have become popular in businesses, educational institutions and libraries.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Children may be more susceptible to harm, but most of the research has been done on adults.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] It is recommended that schools and makerspaces consider ventilation, air quality measurements, and engineering controls to reduce indoor exposure.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Filament printers are a major source of volatile organic compounds (VOCs, substances that easily dissolve in the air) and particulate matter (PM, particles that remain suspended in the air for a long time).
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] 3D printers emit ultrafine particles (in the order of magnitude 1 to 100 nanometers), and research has shown that these are small enough to lodge deep in the respiratory system and be difficult for the body to get rid of.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Some specific VOCs that have been measured from 3D printing include lactide, styrene, ethylbenzene, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, nonanal, tetrahydrofuran, cyclohexanone, butanone, crotonaldehyde, acrylic acid, hydroxyethyl acrylate and methyl methacrylate.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The place of printing should be well ventilated, which can be difficult since good printing often depends on a consistent room temperature and minimal drafts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Air quality can be measured with an air quality meter that can detect VOC and particulate matter.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Printers should not be placed in bedrooms or living rooms, but instead in other places where people do not spend much time, such as in a heated garage, basement or attic.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] The amount of dust in the printing environment should also be limited, for example by vacuuming more often.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Some people place the printer in a cabinet with an exhaust fan through a HEPA filter or activated carbon, but these filters do not remove all particles and exhaust gases.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Exhaust to the outdoor air may be beneficial.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] Lower temperatures in the hotend can produce less emissions, but can also result in poorer print quality.
[src:additive-manufacturing/fused-filament-fabrication] One can choose materials that are less harmful, for example PLA has a reputation for being safer than ABS (but still emits harmful substances).
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] The first methods for rapid prototyping became available in mid 1987 and were used to produce models and prototype parts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Today, they are used for a wide range of applications and are used to manufacture production-quality parts in relatively small numbers if desired without the typical unfavorable short-run economics.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] This economy has encouraged online service bureaus.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Historical surveys of RP technology start with discussions of simulacra production techniques used by 19th-century sculptors.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Some modern sculptors use the progeny technology to produce exhibitions and various objects.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] The ability to reproduce designs from a dataset has given rise to issues of rights, as it is now possible to interpolate volumetric data from 2D images.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] As with CNC subtractive methods, the computer-aided-design – computer-aided manufacturing CAD -CAM workflow in the traditional rapid prototyping process starts with the creation of geometric data, either as a 3D solid using a CAD workstation, or 2D slices using a scanning device.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] For rapid prototyping this data must represent a valid geometric model; namely, one whose boundary surfaces enclose a finite volume, contain no holes exposing the interior, and do not fold back on themselves.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] In other words, the object must have an "inside".
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] The model is valid if for each point in 3D space the computer can determine uniquely whether that point lies inside, on, or outside the boundary surface of the model.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Rapid prototyping is also commonly applied in software engineering to try out new business models and application architectures such as Aerospace, Automotive, Financial Services, Product development, and Healthcare.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Aerospace design and industrial teams rely on prototyping in order to create new AM methodologies in the industry.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Using SLA they can quickly make multiple versions of their projects in a few days and begin testing quicker.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Rapid Prototyping allows designers/developers to provide an accurate idea of how the finished product will turn out before putting too much time and money into the prototype.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] 3D printing being used for Rapid Prototyping allows for Industrial 3D printing to take place.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] With this, you could have large-scale moulds to spare parts being pumped out quickly within a short period of time.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] In the 1970s, Joseph Henry Condon and others at Bell Labs developed the Unix Circuit Design System (UCDS), automating the laborious and error-prone task of manually converting drawings to fabricate circuit boards for the purposes of research and development.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] By the 1980s, U.S. policy makers and industrial managers were forced to take note that America's dominance in the field of machine tool manufacturing evaporated, in what was named the machine tool crisis.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Numerous projects sought to counter these trends in the traditional CNC CAM area, which had begun in the US.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Later when Rapid Prototyping Systems moved out of labs to be commercialized, it was recognized that developments were already international and U.S. rapid prototyping companies would not have the luxury of letting a lead slip away.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] One such report was the 1997 *Rapid Prototyping in Europe and Japan Panel Report* in which Joseph J.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] "The Origins of Rapid Prototyping - RP stems from the ever-growing CAD industry, more specifically, the solid modeling side of CAD.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Before solid modeling was introduced in the late 1980's, three-dimensional models were created with wire frames and surfaces.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] But not until the development of true solid modeling could innovative processes such as RP be developed.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Charles Hull, who helped found 3D Systems in 1986, developed the first RP process.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] This process, called stereolithography, builds objects by curing thin consecutive layers of certain ultraviolet light-sensitive liquid resins with a low-power laser.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] With the introduction of RP, CAD solid models could suddenly come to life".
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] The technologies referred to as Solid Freeform Fabrication are what we recognize today as rapid prototyping, 3D printing or additive manufacturing: Swainson (1977), Schwerzel (1984) worked on polymerization of a photosensitive polymer at the intersection of two computer controlled laser beams.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Ciraud (1972) considered magnetostatic or electrostatic deposition with electron beam, laser or plasma for sintered surface cladding.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] These were all proposed but it is unknown if working machines were built.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Hideo Kodama of Nagoya Municipal Industrial Research Institute was the first to publish an account of a solid model fabricated using a photopolymer rapid prototyping system (1981).
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] The first 3D rapid prototyping system relying on Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) was made in April 1992 by Stratasys but the patent did not issue until June 9, 1992.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Sanders Prototype, Inc introduced the first desktop inkjet 3D Printer (3DP) using an invention from August 4, 1992 (Helinski), Modelmaker 6Pro in late 1993 and then the larger industrial 3D printer, Modelmaker 2, in 1997.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Z-Corp using the MIT 3DP powder binding for Direct Shell Casting (DSP) invented 1993 was introduced to the market in 1995.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Even at that early date the technology was seen as having a place in manufacturing practice.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] A low resolution, low strength output had value in design verification, mold making, production jigs and other areas.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Outputs have steadily advanced toward higher specification uses.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] (Solidscape) started as a Rapid Prototyping 3D Printing manufacturer with the Modelmaker 6Pro for making sacrificial Thermoplastic patterns of CAD models uses Drop-On-Demand (DOD) inkjet single nozzle technology.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Research in rapid prototyping (RP) focuses on increasing production speeds and adapting the technology for mass-manufacturing applications.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] As with computer numerical control (CNC) technologies, the development of open-source software has created an end-to-end CAD-CAM toolchain.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] This has supported a community of manufacturers producing low-resolution devices.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Hobbyist use has also expanded to include more complex laser-based designs.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] The earliest list of RP Processes or Fabrication Technologies published in 1993 was written by Marshall Burns and explains each process very thoroughly.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] It also names some technologies that were precursors to the names on the list below.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] For Example: Visual Impact Corporation only produced a prototype printer for wax deposition and then licensed the patent to Sanders Prototype, Inc instead.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] BPM used the same inkjets and materials.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] It **accelerates the design process** of any product as it allows for both low fidelity prototyping and high fidelity prototyping, to foresee the necessary adjustments to be made before the final production line.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] As a result of this, it also **cuts production costs** for the overall product development and allows **functionality testing** at a fraction of the regular cost.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] It eliminates the risk of the design team suffering injuries and the prototype from getting damaged during the modeling process.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] It also allows users or focus groups to have an involvement in the design process through interactions with each of the prototypes, from the initial prototype to the final model.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] For example: rapid tooling manufacturing process based on CNC machining prototypes, making the mold manufacturing cost reduction, shorten the mold manufacturing cycle, with easier to promote the application of the realization of the mold making process flow and other advantages.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Furthermore, it is an ideal way to test for **ergonomics** and **anthropometry** (*human factors*) so that the designed product is capable of fulfilling the user's needs and offers a unique experience of usage.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] Also, the initial cost of using this production technique can be **expensive** due to the *technology,* which it works with.
[src:additive-manufacturing/rapid-prototyping] It can limit the range of materials, which the product can be made with and depending on the level of complexity that the design entails, it can lead to *hard skill labor*.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Stereolithography is an early and widely-used 3D printing technology.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] In the early 1980s, Japanese researcher Hideo Kodama first invented the modern layered approach to stereolithography by using ultraviolet light to cure photosensitive polymers.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] In 1984, just before Chuck Hull filed his own patent, Alain Le Mehaute, Olivier de Witte, and Jean Claude André, filed a patent for the stereolithography process.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] The French inventors' patent application was abandoned by the French General Electric Company (now Alcatel-Alsthom) and CILAS (The Laser Consortium).
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Le Mehaute believes that the abandonment reflects a problem with innovation in France.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] The term “stereolithography” (Greek: stereo-solid and lithography) was coined in 1984 by Chuck Hull when he filed his patent for the process.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Hull patented stereolithography as a method of creating 3D objects by successively "printing" thin layers of an object using a medium curable by ultraviolet light, starting from the bottom layer to the top layer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Hull's patent described a concentrated beam of ultraviolet light focused onto the surface of a vat filled with a liquid photopolymer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] The beam is focused onto the surface of the liquid photopolymer, creating each layer of the desired 3D object by means of crosslinking (generation of intermolecular bonds in polymers).
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] It was invented with the intent of allowing engineers to create prototypes of their designs in a more time effective manner.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] After the patent was granted in 1986, Hull co-founded the world's first 3D printing company, 3D Systems, to commercialize it.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Stereolithography's success in the automotive industry allowed 3D printing to achieve industry status and the technology continues to find innovative uses in many fields of study.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Attempts have been made to construct mathematical models of stereolithography processes and to design algorithms to determine whether a proposed object may be constructed using 3D printing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Stereolithography is an additive manufacturing process that, in its most common form, works by focusing an ultraviolet (UV) laser on to a vat of photopolymer resin.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] With the help of computer-aided manufacturing or computer-aided design (CAM/CAD) software, the UV laser is used to draw a pre-programmed design or shape on to the surface of the photopolymer vat.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Photopolymers are sensitive to ultraviolet light, so the resin is photochemically solidified and forms a single layer of the desired 3D object.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Then, the build platform lowers one layer and a blade recoats the top of the tank with resin.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] This process is repeated for each layer of the design until the 3D object is complete.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Completed parts must be washed with a solvent to clean wet resin from their surfaces.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] It is also possible to print objects "bottom up" by using a vat with a transparent bottom and focusing the UV or deep-blue polymerization laser upward through the bottom of the vat.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] An inverted stereolithography machine starts a print by lowering the build platform to touch the bottom of the resin-filled vat, then moving upward the height of one layer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] The UV laser then writes the bottom-most layer of the desired part through the transparent vat bottom.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Then the vat is "rocked", flexing and peeling the bottom of the vat away from the hardened photopolymer; the hardened material detaches from the bottom of the vat and stays attached to the rising build platform, and new liquid photopolymer flows in from the edges of the partially built part.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] The UV laser then writes the second-from-bottom layer and repeats the process.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] An advantage of this bottom-up mode is that the build volume can be much bigger than the vat itself, and only enough photopolymer is needed to keep the bottom of the build vat continuously full of photopolymer.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] This approach is typical of desktop SLA printers, while the right-side-up approach is more common in industrial systems.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Stereolithography requires the use of supporting structures which attach to the elevator platform to prevent deflection due to gravity, resist lateral pressure from the resin-filled blade, or retain newly created sections during the "vat rocking" of bottom-up printing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Supports are typically created automatically during the preparation of CAD models and can also be made manually.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] In either situation, the supports must be removed manually after printing.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Other forms of stereolithography build each layer by LCD masking, or using a DLP projector.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] The liquid materials used for SLA printing are commonly referred to as "resins" and are thermoset polymers.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] A wide variety of resins are commercially available, and it is also possible to use homemade resins.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Material properties vary according to formulation configurations: "materials can be soft or hard, heavily filled with secondary materials like glass and ceramic, or imbued with mechanical properties like high heat deflection temperature or impact resistance".
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Recently, some studies have tested the possibility to green or reusable materials to produce "sustainable" resins.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Stereolithographic models have been used in medicine since the 1990s, for creating accurate 3D models of various anatomical regions of a patient, based on data from computer scans.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Medical modelling involves first acquiring a CT, MRI, or other scan.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] This data consists of a series of cross-sectional images of the human anatomy.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] In these images, different tissues show up as different levels of grey.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Selecting a range of grey values enables specific tissues to be isolated.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] A region of interest is then selected and all the pixels connected to the target point within that grey value range are selected.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] This enables a specific organ to be selected.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] The segmented data may then be translated into a format suitable for stereolithography.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] While stereolithography is normally accurate, the accuracy of a medical model depends on many factors, especially the operator performing the segmentation correctly.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] There are potential errors possible when making medical models using stereolithography, but these can be avoided with practice and well-trained operators.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Stereolithographic models are used as an aid to diagnosis, preoperative planning, and implant design and manufacture.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] This might involve planning and rehearsing osteotomies, for example.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Surgeons use models to help plan surgeries, and prosthetists and technologists also use models as an aid to the design and manufacture of custom-fitting implants.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] For instance, medical models created through stereolithography can be used to help in the construction of cranioplasty plates.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] In 2019, scientists at Rice University published an article in the journal *Science*, presenting soft hydrogel materials for stereolithography used in biological research applications.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Stereolithography is often used for prototyping parts.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] For a relatively low price, stereolithography can produce accurate prototypes, even of irregular shapes.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Businesses can use those prototypes to assess the design of their product or as publicity for the final product.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] One of the advantages of stereolithography is its speed; functional parts can be manufactured within a day.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] The length of time it takes to produce a single part depends upon the complexity of the design and the size.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Printing time can last anywhere from hours to more than a day.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] A unique advantage of LCD-based SLA systems is that additional detail or material in a given layer does not meaningfully increase print time, allowing great time savings on multiple parts if there is space to combine them in a single print.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] SLA-printed parts, unlike those obtained from FFF/FDM, do not exhibit significant anisotropy (structural non-uniformity) and minimal visible layering pattern.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] The surface quality is, in general, superior.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Prototypes and designs made with stereolithography are strong enough to be machined and can also be used to make master patterns for injection molding or various metal casting processes.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Although stereolithography can be used to produce virtually any synthetic design, cost has historically been a disadvantage compared to FFF, though the price is coming down.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Since 2012, public interest in 3D printing has inspired the design of several consumer SLA machines which are closer in price to other technologies.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Beginning in 2016, substitution of the SLA and DLP methods with a high-resolution, high-contrast LCD panel has brought prices below US$200.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] SLA prints require hands-on post-processing steps (washing, drying, curing, and possibly removing support material) that are not needed with other methods.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] Another disadvantage is that the photopolymers are sticky and messy, and need to be handled with care.
[src:additive-manufacturing/stereolithography] The choice of materials is limited compared to FFF, which can process virtually any thermoplastic.
